NOTES_GALATIANS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: Apóstolos (G652) means "one sent forth" — a commissioned agent with full authority of the sender. Paul\'s emphatic double negation (ouk...oude) stresses his apostleship originates neither collectively from men (anthrōpōn, plural) nor through any individual man (anthrōpou, singular), but directly through Jesus Christ and God the Father. The participle egeírantos ("having raised") ties Paul\'s commission inseparably to the resurrection event. THEOLOGICAL: By pairing Jesus Christ with God the Father as the dual source of his apostleship, Paul places Christ on the same plane of divine authority as the Father — a profound Christological claim in the letter\'s very first verse.',
        4: 'GREEK: Exelētai (G1807, aorist middle subjunctive of exairéō) means "to rescue, to pluck out, to deliver." This is a forceful extraction term. The phrase aiōnos tou enestōtos ponērou ("the present evil age") reflects Jewish apocalyptic categories of two ages — the present age under evil dominion and the age to come. THEOLOGICAL: Christ\'s self-giving is substitutionary (hypér, "on behalf of") and liberating — a rescue operation from the domain of the present evil age. This is accomplished not by human will but katá to thélēma ("according to the will") of God the Father. TYPOLOGY: Echoes the Exodus deliverance pattern — God rescuing his people from bondage (Ex 6:6), now fulfilled in Christ\'s atoning work delivering from sin\'s dominion.',
        6: 'GREEK: Metatíthesthe (G3346) means "to transfer, to transpose, to desert." In secular Greek it described political or philosophical defection. Tachéōs ("so quickly") expresses Paul\'s astonishment at the speed of their apostasy. Héteron euangélion ("a different gospel") uses héteros (different in kind), not állos (another of the same kind), signaling a qualitative departure. HISTORICAL: The troublers were likely Judaizers who insisted Gentile converts must adopt Torah observance — circumcision, dietary laws, and calendar — for full covenant membership.',
        8: 'GREEK: Anáthema (G331) derives from the Hebrew ḥērem — that which is devoted to destruction, placed under the ban of God. In the LXX this term denotes what is irrevocably given over to divine judgment (cf. Josh 6:17-18, Deut 7:26). THEOLOGICAL: The gravity of Paul\'s pronouncement is staggering — he includes even himself (hēmeîs, "we") and heavenly angels under this curse should they alter the gospel. This establishes the gospel\'s content as transcending all human and angelic authority. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The mention of an angel (ángelos) from heaven potentially distorting God\'s message echoes the divine council theme where spiritual beings can act contrary to God\'s purposes (cf. 1 Kings 22:19-23, 2 Cor 11:14).',
        12: 'GREEK: Apokalýpseōs (G602, from apó + kalýptō, "to unveil, to uncover") denotes a divine disclosure of what was previously hidden. THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s gospel came not through human tradition (paralambánō, "receive by transmission") nor through didactic instruction (didáskō, "taught"), but by direct, unmediated revelation from Jesus Christ. The genitive Iēsoû Christoû is likely both subjective (Christ revealed it) and objective (Christ was its content). This parallels the revelation granted to OT prophets directly by God (cf. Amos 3:7, Jer 1:4-5).',
        15: 'GREEK: Aphorísas (G873) means "to mark off by boundaries, to set apart." TYPOLOGY: Paul\'s language of being set apart from the womb directly echoes the prophetic calling of Jeremiah (Jer 1:5 LXX) and the Servant of the Lord (Isa 49:1). Paul sees his apostolic commission as standing in continuity with Israel\'s prophetic tradition — appointed before birth to a specific divine mission. The phrase ek koilías mētros ("from the womb of my mother") underscores God\'s sovereign, pre-temporal election.',
        16: 'GREEK: Apokalýpsai ton huion autoû en emoí — "to reveal his Son in me." The preposition en may be locative ("within me," an inward revelation) or instrumental ("through me," for proclamation). Both senses likely operate simultaneously. Éthnos (G1484) here means "nations/Gentiles." THEOLOGICAL: The content of divine revelation is not a proposition but a Person — God\'s Son. Paul\'s encounter with the risen Christ was simultaneously his conversion and his commissioning to the nations. Sarkí kaí haímati ("flesh and blood") is a Semitic idiom for mere human counsel (cf. Matt 16:17).',
        18: 'GREEK: Historēsai (G2477) is a rare term meaning "to visit in order to inquire, to get to know personally." This is its only NT occurrence. It implies a purposeful, investigative visit — not to receive apostolic authorization but to become acquainted with Cephas (Kēphâs, Aramaic for "Rock," = Peter). HISTORICAL: The three-year gap after Paul\'s conversion places this Jerusalem visit around AD 37-38. The fifteen-day stay was brief enough to demonstrate independence yet significant enough to establish fellowship with the chief apostle.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: James (Iákōbon) is identified as ton adelphón toû kyríou — "the brother of the Lord." This designation confirms both the historical existence of Jesus\' biological family and James\'s subsequent rise to leadership in the Jerusalem assembly (cf. Acts 15:13, Acts 21:18). Paul\'s mention of seeing only Peter and James among the apostles reinforces his argument of independence from the broader apostolic circle. GREEK: The term kýrios (G2962) here applied to Jesus carries its full weight as the title of sovereign authority, echoing its LXX usage for the God of Israel.',
        23: 'GREEK: The direct quotation preserves early Christian oral tradition about Paul\'s dramatic transformation. Pístis (G4102) here means "the faith" — the objective content of Christian belief, not merely subjective trust. Epórthei (G4199, imperfect tense of porthéō) means "was ravaging, was destroying" — the same verb used in v.13 for Paul\'s persecution. TYPOLOGY: The persecutor becoming proclaimer of the very faith he sought to annihilate serves as a living demonstration of the transformative power of the gospel and of sovereign grace — the ultimate reversal narrative.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'GREEK: ἀποκάλυψιν (apokalypsin, Strong\'s G602) means "revelation" or "unveiling"—Paul stresses that his journey was directed by divine disclosure, not human initiative. The verb ἀνεθέμην (anethemēn, G394) means "to lay before" or "to communicate," a term used for formal consultation. THEOLOGICAL: Paul submits his gospel for examination not out of uncertainty but out of strategic concern that his apostolic labor among the nations not be undermined.',
        4: 'GREEK: παρεισάκτους (pareisaktous, G3920) is a rare term meaning "smuggled in, secretly introduced"—a hapax legomenon in the NT. ψευδαδέλφους (pseudadelphous, G5569) means "false brothers." THEOLOGICAL: These infiltrators sought to spy out (κατασκοπῆσαι, G2684, a military espionage term) the freedom believers possess in Christ Jesus, with the aim of re-enslaving them under the law. The language of liberty versus bondage echoes the Exodus typology.',
        6: 'GREEK: πρόσωπον ἀνθρώπου οὐ λαμβάνει is a Semitic idiom from the LXX meaning "God does not show partiality" or "receive the face of a man" (cf. Deut 10:17; Acts 10:34). THEOLOGICAL: Paul invokes divine impartiality to relativize human ecclesiastical authority—the Jerusalem pillars\' status adds nothing to his commission from the risen Christ.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: James (the brother of the Lord), Cephas (Peter), and John are designated στῦλοι (stȳloi, "pillars," G4769), a term evoking the pillars of the Temple (cf. 1 Kgs 7:21; Rev 3:12). THEOLOGICAL: The right hand of fellowship (δεξιὰς κοινωνίας) formally ratified a recognized division of apostolic labor—Paul and Barnabas to the nations, the Jerusalem apostles to the circumcision—without any subordination of Paul\'s gospel.',
        11: 'HISTORICAL: Antioch was the first major center of mixed Jewish-Gentile Christian community (Acts 11:19-26). Cephas\'s visit and subsequent withdrawal created a crisis that threatened the unity of the body of Christ across ethnic lines. GREEK: κατεγνωσμένος (kategnōsmenos, G2607) is a perfect passive participle meaning "having been condemned" or "standing self-condemned"—his own prior conduct condemned him.',
        14: 'GREEK: ὀρθοποδοῦσιν (orthopodousin, G3716) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to walk uprightly" or "to walk with straight feet"—a vivid metaphor for doctrinal and ethical consistency. Ἰουδαΐζειν (Ioudaïzein, G2450) is also rare, meaning "to adopt Jewish customs" or "to Judaize." THEOLOGICAL: Paul publicly confronts Peter because the truth of the gospel—that nations are accepted in Christ apart from Torah-observance—was at stake, not merely social etiquette.',
        16: 'GREEK: The phrase πίστεως Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ is a genitive construction that may be rendered "faith in Jesus Christ" (objective genitive) or "faithfulness of Jesus Christ" (subjective genitive). The formal equivalence preserves the ambiguity as "faithfulness of," reflecting Christ\'s own covenant fidelity. THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the theological heart of Galatians—justification (δικαιοῦται, G1344) comes not ἐξ ἔργων νόμου ("out of works of law") but through Christ. The final clause echoes Ps 143:2 (LXX 142:2): "no flesh shall be justified." TYPOLOGY: The contrast between law and faith recapitulates the Abraham narrative Paul will develop in ch. 3 (cf. Gen 15:6).',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Through law I died to law" expresses the paradox that the law itself, by exposing sin and pronouncing the curse (cf. Gal 3:13), brought about Paul\'s death to its regime—so that he might live to God. GREEK: συνεσταύρωμαι (synestaurōmai, G4957) is a perfect passive: "I have been co-crucified with Christ"—the perfect tense indicating an abiding state resulting from a past event. This is the believer\'s union with Christ in His death.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse articulates the doctrine of union with Christ in its most personal and concentrated form. The old self has died with Christ; the new life is Christ Himself living in the believer. GREEK: The phrase τῇ τοῦ υἱοῦ τοῦ θεοῦ ("of the Son of God") is a high Christological title—Paul grounds daily existence in the faithfulness of One who is fully divine. The participles ἀγαπήσαντός (having loved) and παραδόντος (having given over) point to the cross as the supreme act of love (cf. Rom 8:32; Eph 5:2, 25).',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s closing statement forms a devastating logical conclusion: if righteousness (δικαιοσύνη, G1343) could come through law, then Christ\'s death was δωρεάν (dōrean, G1432)—"gratuitously," "for nothing," "without cause." To revert to law-righteousness is to nullify (ἀθετέω, G114) the grace of God and render the cross purposeless. This directly challenges Peter\'s behavior and the Judaizers\' theology.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Bewitched" (ἐβάσκανεν, ebaskanen, Strong\'s G940) refers to casting the evil eye or a spell — a vivid metaphor for the persuasive power of the Judaizing teachers. "Publicly portrayed" (προεγράφη, proegraphē, G4270) means to write or placard before the public eye, as in a public notice; Paul\'s preaching made the crucifixion visually vivid to them.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul frames the entire debate around the reception of the Spirit as empirical evidence. "Hearing of faith" (ἀκοῆς πίστεως) can mean either "the hearing that comes from faith" or "the message that produces faith" — both readings underscore that the Spirit came apart from Torah observance. This directly parallels the Pentecost experience in Acts 2 and the Gentile reception in Acts 10:44-48.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul quotes Genesis 15:6 (LXX) — the foundational text establishing that Abraham was declared righteous by faith prior to circumcision (Gen 17) and prior to the giving of the law (Ex 19-20). This becomes the paradigmatic pattern: covenant relationship with God is established through trust, not through works of Torah. GREEK: ἐλογίσθη (elogisthē, G3049) is an accounting term meaning "reckoned" or "credited to one\'s account."',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Scripture, having foreseen" (προϊδοῦσα ἡ γραφή) personifies Scripture as a prophetic agent, identifying it with the voice of God Himself. The quotation combines Genesis 12:3 and 18:18 (LXX). TYPOLOGY: The promise to Abraham that "all the nations" (πάντα τὰ ἔθνη) would be blessed is the proto-evangelion of Gentile inclusion, fulfilled in the mission of Christ and the apostolic proclamation.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul quotes Deuteronomy 27:26 (LXX) to demonstrate that the law-system demands total, unbroken obedience — anything less places one under a covenantal curse. This is not an argument against the law\'s goodness but against its sufficiency as a means of justification. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The curse (κατάρα, katara) invokes the covenant lawsuit motif of Deuteronomy 28-32, where heaven and earth are called as witnesses against Israel.',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul quotes Deuteronomy 21:23 (LXX). Christ becomes the embodiment of the Torah\'s curse in a substitutionary act — "having become a curse on our behalf" (γενόμενος ὑπὲρ ἡμῶν κατάρα). The "tree" (ξύλον, xylon, G3586) connects to the cross and echoes both the cursed tree of Eden and the bronze serpent lifted on a pole (Num 21:8-9; John 3:14). GREEK: ἐξηγόρασεν (exēgorasen, G1805) means "bought out of the marketplace" — a slave-redemption term.',
        16: 'GREEK: Paul makes a grammatical argument based on the singular σπέρματι (spermati, "seed," G4690) in Genesis 13:15, 17:8 (LXX). While "seed" is naturally a collective singular in both Hebrew (זֶרַע) and Greek, Paul reads it christologically as pointing to one ultimate descendant. TYPOLOGY: Christ is the singular Seed of Abraham in whom all the covenant promises find their fulfillment and through whom the Abrahamic blessing flows to all nations (Gen 22:18; 2 Sam 7:12-14).',
        19: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The law was "ordained through angels" (διαταγεὶς δι\' ἀγγέλων) — reflecting a widespread Second Temple Jewish tradition (cf. Acts 7:38, 53; Heb 2:2; Jubilees 1:27-29; Josephus, Ant. 15.136) that angelic beings mediated the Sinai covenant. This places the law at one remove from God\'s direct promise to Abraham, establishing its secondary and temporary role. GREEK: μεσίτης (mesitēs, G3316) refers to a go-between or intermediary, traditionally understood as Moses.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Scripture shut up all things under sin" (συνέκλεισεν ἡ γραφὴ τὰ πάντα ὑπὸ ἁμαρτίαν) means the law functioned to imprison the entire cosmos under the diagnosis of sin, so that the only available exit would be the promise realized through faith in Jesus Christ. GREEK: συνέκλεισεν (synekleisen, G4788) means "enclosed together" or "locked up on all sides" — emphasizing the comprehensive and inescapable nature of sin\'s dominion apart from Christ.',
        24: 'GREEK: παιδαγωγός (paidagōgos, G3807) was not a "teacher" but a household slave who escorted children to school and supervised their conduct — a custodian with disciplinary authority. The term implies both protective custody and temporary subordination. THEOLOGICAL: The law\'s role was provisional, leading to Christ (εἰς Χριστόν) — either "until Christ came" (temporal) or "toward Christ" (teleological). Both senses are likely intended: the law both pointed forward to and gave way to Christ.',
        28: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is one of the most sweeping statements of new-creation unity in the New Testament. The three pairs — Jew/Greek, slave/free, male/female — correspond to fundamental social divisions in the ancient world. The phrase "not male and female" (οὐκ ἔνι ἄρσεν καὶ θῆλυ) deliberately echoes Genesis 1:27 LXX, suggesting that in Christ a new humanity is inaugurated that transcends even the primal created distinctions in terms of standing before God. STRUCTURE: The shift from οὐδέ ("nor") in the first two pairs to καί ("and") in the third pair signals the direct Genesis allusion.',
        29: 'TYPOLOGY: The chapter\'s argument reaches its climax: Gentile believers who belong to Christ are thereby Abraham\'s seed and heirs of the covenant promise — not through Torah observance or ethnic lineage but through union with the singular Seed, Christ (v. 16). THEOLOGICAL: κληρονόμοι (klēronomoi, G2818) — "heirs" — carries the full weight of Israel\'s inheritance language, now applied to all who are in Christ, fulfilling the Abrahamic covenant\'s universal scope (Gen 12:3; Rom 4:13-16).',
    },
    4: {
        3: 'GREEK: "stoicheia tou kosmou" (στοιχεῖα τοῦ κόσμου, Strong\'s G4747) — "elements of the world" — refers to rudimentary principles or elemental forces. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In Second Temple Judaism, this phrase carried connotations of spiritual powers or beings governing the nations (cf. Deut 32:8 LXX; Dan 10:13), suggesting that Torah observance apart from Christ places one under the dominion of lesser spiritual authorities rather than the Most High God.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The fullness of the time" (τὸ πλήρωμα τοῦ χρόνου) marks God\'s sovereignly appointed moment in redemptive history. "Sent forth" (ἐξαπέστειλεν, G1821) implies pre-existence and divine commissioning — the Son was sent from the Father\'s presence. "Having come into being from a woman" (γενόμενον ἐκ γυναικός) affirms true incarnation. TYPOLOGY: Echoes Genesis 3:15 — the seed of the woman — and fulfills the promise that through Abraham\'s seed all nations would be blessed (Gen 12:3; Gal 3:16).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Redeem" (ἐξαγοράσῃ, G1805) means to buy out of the marketplace — a slave-purchase metaphor indicating complete liberation. "Adoption as sons" (υἱοθεσίαν, G5206) is a Roman legal term for the formal placement of an heir into full sonship rights. THEOLOGICAL: The double purpose clause ("in order that...in order that") shows Christ\'s redemptive work has both a negative aim (liberation from Law\'s curse) and a positive aim (bestowal of filial status).',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: The sending of the Spirit parallels the sending of the Son in v.4, establishing a Trinitarian pattern: God the Father sends the Son and the Spirit. "Abba" (Ἀββᾶ) is Aramaic for "Father" — an intimate familial address. GREEK: "Crying out" (κρᾶζον, G2896) is a strong, loud exclamation, suggesting the Spirit\'s testimony within believers is not quiet assent but powerful, confident proclamation of filial identity (cf. Rom 8:15-16).',
        8: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Those which by nature are not gods" (τοῖς φύσει μὴ οὖσι θεοῖς) — Paul acknowledges that the Galatians\' former pagan worship was directed at beings that exist but are not truly God by nature. This aligns with the divine council worldview where lesser spiritual beings (elohim) received the nations\' worship (Deut 32:17; Ps 96:5 LXX), yet are ontologically inferior to the one true God.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Weak and beggarly elements" (ἀσθενῆ καὶ πτωχὰ στοιχεῖα) — Paul stunningly equates returning to Torah-observance as a covenant requirement with returning to pagan worship, since both place one under the stoicheia. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "having become known by God" (γνωσθέντες ὑπὸ θεοῦ) corrects any notion that human initiative drives salvation — it is God\'s sovereign knowing and choosing that is primary (cf. 1 Cor 8:3).',
        14: 'GREEK: "Reject with contempt" translates ἐξεπτύσατε (ekeptysate, G1609) — literally "spit out," a hapax legomenon in the NT. In the ancient world, spitting was an apotropaic gesture to ward off evil or disease. HISTORICAL: Paul\'s bodily affliction evidently could have provoked revulsion, yet the Galatians received him as a messenger (angelos) of God — indeed as Christ Jesus Himself, showing the highest conceivable honor.',
        19: 'GREEK: "Travail in birth" (ὠδίνω, G5605) — Paul uses maternal imagery for his apostolic labor. "Until Christ be formed (μορφωθῇ, G3445) in you" — morphoō implies the inward shaping of Christ\'s very nature within believers. THEOLOGICAL: This is one of the most profound statements of Paul\'s understanding of sanctification: it is not merely behavioral conformity but the ontological formation of Christ\'s character and life within the believing community.',
        24: 'GREEK: "Being spoken allegorically" (ἀλληγορούμενα, G238) — the only use of this term in the NT. Paul does not deny the historicity of the Genesis account but discerns a deeper typological correspondence. TYPOLOGY: Hagar-Sinai-present Jerusalem represents the covenant of law producing bondage; Sarah-promise-heavenly Jerusalem represents the covenant of grace producing freedom. The two covenants correspond to two ages of redemptive history.',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Jerusalem above" (ἡ ἄνω Ἱερουσαλήμ) reflects Jewish apocalyptic expectation of a heavenly city prepared by God (cf. Heb 12:22; Rev 21:2). Paul identifies this free, heavenly Jerusalem as the true mother of all believers, both Jew and Gentile. TYPOLOGY: This corresponds to Sarah, the free woman, and to the new covenant promise — the eschatological city is present reality for those in Christ, not merely a future hope.',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: Quoted from Isaiah 54:1 (LXX), originally addressed to barren Zion after exile. Paul applies it to the new covenant community — the formerly "barren" Gentile church now produces more children than the synagogue under the old covenant. The prophetic oracle thus finds its ultimate fulfillment in the ingathering of the nations through Christ.',
        30: 'TYPOLOGY: Quoted from Genesis 21:10 — the words of Sarah to Abraham. Paul treats Scripture itself as the speaking authority ("what does the Scripture say?"). The expulsion of Ishmael typologically prefigures the ultimate incompatibility of law-based covenant membership with promise-based inheritance. THEOLOGICAL: The inheritance belongs exclusively to the children of the free woman — those who are in Christ by faith, not those who seek justification through Torah observance.',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'GREEK: "ἐλευθερίᾳ" (eleutheria, Strong\'s G1657) denotes freedom or liberty, here a dative of advantage or purpose. "στήκετε" (stēkete, G4739) is a late Koine form meaning "stand firm," carrying the sense of resolute posture. The verse forms a hinge between Paul\'s allegory of Sarah and Hagar (ch. 4) and the practical exhortation that follows. THEOLOGICAL: Christian freedom is not self-achieved but granted by Christ\'s redemptive work; returning to Torah-observance for justification is reimposing the Sinai covenant yoke (Acts 15:10).',
        4: 'GREEK: "κατηργήθητε" (katērgēthēte, G2673) is aorist passive of katargeō, meaning "to be rendered ineffective, severed, nullified." "ἐξεπέσατε" (exepesate, G1601) means "to fall out of, fall away from." THEOLOGICAL: Paul does not describe loss of salvation per se but a functional severance — those seeking justification through Torah have displaced themselves from the sphere of grace wherein Christ operates. The two systems of justification are mutually exclusive.',
        6: 'GREEK: "ἐνεργουμένη" (energoumenē, G1754) is a middle/passive participle of energeō — faith that is "being made effective" or "working itself out" through love. THEOLOGICAL: This verse is pivotal in the faith-works debate. Paul affirms that saving faith is not inert but is actuated through love (agapē), bridging the seeming tension between Paul and James (Jas 2:17-26). Neither the covenant sign of circumcision nor its absence has power; only faith expressing itself through love avails.',
        9: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul draws on the Passover imagery of leaven removal (Exod 12:15; 1 Cor 5:6-8). In Jewish practice, leaven was purged before Passover as a symbol of corruption. Here, the "little leaven" represents the false teaching of the Judaizers — even a small doctrinal corruption spreads through the whole community.',
        12: 'GREEK: "ἀποκόψονται" (apokopsontai, G609) means "to cut off" — Paul uses biting irony: if the agitators are so zealous for circumcision, let them go further and mutilate themselves entirely. HISTORICAL: This likely alludes to the castration rites of the Cybele cult priests (Galli) well known in Asia Minor, making the sarcasm particularly sharp for a Galatian audience.',
        14: 'TYPOLOGY: Paul quotes Lev 19:18 (LXX: "Ἀγαπήσεις τὸν πλησίον σου ὡς σεαυτόν"), the same command Jesus identified as the second greatest commandment (Matt 22:39; Mark 12:31). "πεπλήρωται" (peplērōtai, G4137) is perfect passive — the law stands fulfilled, completed in its deepest intent through this single word. THEOLOGICAL: The law finds its telos not in ritual observance but in self-giving love — the very principle embodied in Christ\'s cross.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: The flesh-Spirit antithesis is not Greek dualism of body versus soul but reflects Paul\'s eschatological framework: the old age (sarx) and the new age (pneuma) overlap in the present. The believer lives at the intersection of these two ages. "ἀντίκειται" (antikeitai, G480) means "to be set against, opposed" — the two are in irreconcilable warfare. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The cosmic conflict between the Spirit of God and the domain of the flesh mirrors the broader spiritual warfare between God\'s purposes and rebellious powers (Eph 6:12).',
        21: 'GREEK: "κληρονομήσουσιν" (klēronomēsousin, G2816) means "shall inherit" — a term rooted in Israel\'s inheritance of the Promised Land, now applied to the eschatological kingdom of God. THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s vice list echoes standard Hellenistic and Jewish moral catalogs but is grounded in the warning that persistent, unrepentant practice of these works excludes one from God\'s kingdom inheritance (1 Cor 6:9-10; Eph 5:5).',
        22: 'GREEK: "καρπός" (karpos, G2590) is singular — "fruit," not "fruits." This is deliberate: the Spirit produces a unified cluster of virtues, not isolated traits. THEOLOGICAL: In contrast to the plural "works" (erga) of the flesh, the singular "fruit" emphasizes the organic unity of the Spirit\'s transformative work. These nine qualities reflect the character of Christ Himself and are produced by the indwelling Spirit, not by human moral effort.',
        24: 'GREEK: "ἐσταύρωσαν" (estaurōsan, G4717) is aorist active — "have crucified," a decisive, completed action. TYPOLOGY: The believer\'s crucifixion of the flesh participates in Christ\'s own crucifixion (Gal 2:20). The "passions" (pathēmasin, G3804) and "desires" (epithymiais, G1939) represent the totality of the fallen nature\'s drives. This is the existential application of the cross — not merely a doctrine believed but a reality enacted in the believer\'s life.',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Prolēmphthē" (προλημφθῇ, from prolambánō) means "to be overtaken" or "caught beforehand," suggesting being surprised by sin rather than deliberate transgression. "Katartizete" (καταρτίζετε, Strong\'s G2675) means "to mend, restore, put in order" — the same word used for mending nets in Matt 4:21, carrying a sense of careful repair rather than punishment. THEOLOGICAL: The pneumatikoi ("spiritual ones") are those walking by the Spirit as described in Gal 5:16-25, now given pastoral responsibility.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The law of Christ" (ton nomon tou Christou) is a striking phrase in a letter arguing against Torah-observance for justification. Paul redefines "law" around Christ\'s own command of love (Gal 5:14; John 13:34), showing that freedom from the Mosaic covenant does not mean lawlessness but a higher fulfillment. TYPOLOGY: This echoes the love commandment of Lev 19:18 now fulfilled in and through the Messiah.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Phortion" (φορτίον, Strong\'s G5413) differs from "barē" (βάρη, burdens) in v2. "Barē" suggests crushing, oppressive weights shared communally, while "phortion" denotes one\'s own individual load of responsibility — as of a soldier\'s pack. The two verses are complementary, not contradictory.',
        7: 'GREEK: "Myktērizetai" (μυκτηρίζεται, Strong\'s G3456) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning literally "to turn up the nose at, to sneer at, to mock." It derives from "myktēr" (nose). THEOLOGICAL: Paul states a universal divine principle of sowing and reaping, echoing Prov 22:8 (LXX) and Hos 8:7, grounding ethical exhortation in the character of God who cannot be outwitted.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: The flesh/Spirit antithesis here summarizes the entire argument of Galatians 5-6. "Phthorá" (corruption/decay) stands in absolute contrast to "zōēn aiōnion" (life eternal). The eschatological harvest imagery connects to Dan 12:2 and the final resurrection, making present moral choices carry eternal weight.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: This is the climactic confession of the epistle. "Estaurōtai" (ἐσταύρωται, perfect passive) indicates a completed crucifixion with abiding results — the world stands permanently crucified to Paul, and he to the world. The cross is not merely a historical event but an ongoing reality reshaping all cosmic allegiances. TYPOLOGY: Paul\'s union with Christ\'s cross fulfills his earlier declaration: "I have been crucified with Christ" (Gal 2:20).',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Kainē ktisis" (καινὴ κτίσις, "new creation") is the theological summit of Galatians. Neither Jewish identity marker (circumcision) nor Gentile status (uncircumcision) holds any significance — only the new creation inaugurated by Christ\'s death and resurrection. TYPOLOGY: This echoes Isa 65:17 and 66:22 (new heavens and new earth) and anticipates the consummation of 2 Cor 5:17 and Rev 21:1-5.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The Israel of God" (ton Israēl tou theou) is a debated phrase. In context, Paul likely refers to the true, eschatological Israel composed of all who walk by the rule of new creation — both believing Jews and Gentiles united in Christ. The "kaí" before "upon the Israel of God" may be epexegetical ("that is, the Israel of God"), identifying this community as the covenant people redefined around faith in the Messiah. The blessing echoes Ps 125:5 and Ps 128:6 (LXX).',
        17: 'GREEK: "Stigmata" (στίγματα, Strong\'s G4742) refers to brand-marks, as on slaves or devotees of a deity. HISTORICAL: In the Roman world, slaves and soldiers bore brands of ownership. Paul\'s scars from persecution (2 Cor 11:23-25) serve as visible proof of his belonging to Jesus as Lord, trumping any mark of circumcision that the agitators demand.',
    },
}